1
00:01:15,031 --> 00:01:19,610
4, 5, 6 ...

2
00:01:20,620 --> 00:01:24,119
7, 8. Now, girls ...

3
00:02:35,653 --> 00:02:39,651
Come on, girls. Anybody?

4
00:02:40,992 --> 00:02:42,949
Anybody else?

5
00:02:43,536 --> 00:02:45,078
Jenny, again.

6
00:02:45,580 --> 00:02:47,905
Isn't it because 
Mr. Rochester is blind?

7
00:02:48,666 --> 00:02:49,864
Yes, Jenny.

8
00:02:52,461 --> 00:02:54,703
I've got an English essay to do
by tomorrow morning.

9
00:02:54,797 --> 00:02:58,332
Right. So the only sound I want to
hear coming through the ceiling ...

10
00:02:58,426 --> 00:03:01,462
is the sound of sweat
dripping onto textbooks.

11
00:03:01,554 --> 00:03:03,677
- Cello?
- No cello.

12
00:03:04,473 --> 00:03:06,762
I thought we agreed that
cello was my interest or hobby.

13
00:03:06,851 --> 00:03:09,424
Well, it already is
your interest or hobby.

14
00:03:09,520 --> 00:03:11,643
So when they ask you
at the Oxford interview,

15
00:03:11,731 --> 00:03:13,225
"What is your interest or hobby?"

16
00:03:13,316 --> 00:03:15,522
you can say the cello
and you won't be lying.

17
00:03:15,609 --> 00:03:17,982
But you don't have 
to practice a hobby.

18
00:03:18,529 --> 00:03:19,988
A hobby is a hobby.

19
00:03:20,239 --> 00:03:22,279
Can I stop going
to the youth orchestra, then?

20
00:03:22,533 --> 00:03:25,984
No! No, no, the youth orchestra's
a good thing.

21
00:03:26,078 --> 00:03:30,906
- That shows you're a joiner-inner.
- Yes, but I've already joined in.

22
00:03:31,292 --> 00:03:33,119
So now I can stop.

23
00:03:34,837 --> 00:03:39,298
No! No, that just shows 
the opposite. Don't you see?

24
00:03:39,925 --> 00:03:42,595
No, that shows you're a rebel.
They don't want that at Oxford.

25
00:03:42,678 --> 00:03:45,003
No. They don't want people
who can think for themselves.

26
00:03:45,097 --> 00:03:46,675
No, of course they don't.

27
00:04:28,599 --> 00:04:31,884
- See you Wednesday.
- All right, okay. Bye.

28
00:04:32,686 --> 00:04:37,348
Jenny? Should I wear, 
like, Sunday best?

29
00:04:37,775 --> 00:04:39,103
Better, I'm afraid.

30
00:04:40,402 --> 00:04:44,021
Just to show my father you're
'un jeune homme sérieux', not a Teddy Boy.

31
00:04:44,740 --> 00:04:46,234
God. Right.

32
00:04:49,703 --> 00:04:51,826
I'm going to go. It's going 
to bucket down in a minute.

33
00:04:52,081 --> 00:04:55,035
- Okay, right.
- I'll see you at the weekend.

34
00:04:56,001 --> 00:04:57,793
- Bye, then.
- Bye.

35
00:04:57,878 --> 00:04:59,337
- Sorry.
- Sorry.

36
00:05:01,006 --> 00:05:02,750
Goodbye, my love!

37
00:05:09,056 --> 00:05:10,550
Come on, come on.

38
00:05:10,641 --> 00:05:13,926
- No!
- Stop it now, stop it. That's enough.

39
00:05:14,686 --> 00:05:16,478
Now look what you've done.

40
00:05:18,649 --> 00:05:20,309
Come here.
The nice man's waiting for us.

41
00:05:20,401 --> 00:05:22,310
- It fell off!
- No, it didn't fall off.

42
00:05:22,403 --> 00:05:26,151
- You kicked it off. Now, come on.
- But my sock's all wet!

43
00:05:37,835 --> 00:05:41,085
Hello. Look, if you had any sense,

44
00:05:41,171 --> 00:05:42,582
you wouldn't take a lift
from a strange man,

45
00:05:42,673 --> 00:05:45,294
but I'm a music lover
and I'm worried about your cello,

46
00:05:46,468 --> 00:05:50,086
so what I propose is you put it
in my car and walk alongside me.

47
00:05:52,850 --> 00:05:55,257
How do I know you won't just 
drive off with the cello?

48
00:05:56,478 --> 00:05:58,048
Good point.

49
00:05:59,982 --> 00:06:04,026
How much does a new cello cost?
£10, £15? I don't know.

50
00:06:04,111 --> 00:06:06,518
Let's say 15.

51
00:06:07,698 --> 00:06:09,240
No? All right.

52
00:06:10,909 --> 00:06:12,403
Up to you.

53
00:06:22,212 --> 00:06:24,169
- And that.
- Right.

54
00:06:28,802 --> 00:06:30,296
- I'm David, by the way.
- Jenny.

55
00:06:30,387 --> 00:06:31,881
Very good.

56
00:06:42,607 --> 00:06:45,774
- How did the concert go?
- It was a rehearsal.

57
00:06:45,861 --> 00:06:48,399
- The concert's next Thursday.
- What are you playing?

58
00:06:49,031 --> 00:06:50,321
Elgar.

59
00:06:51,241 --> 00:06:54,361
I think it's a shame he spent so 
much time in Worcester, don't you?

60
00:06:54,453 --> 00:06:57,489
Because Worcester's too near Birmingham,
and you can hear that in the music.

61
00:06:57,914 --> 00:07:00,666
There's a terrible Brummy accent
in there, if you listen hard enough.

62
00:07:04,004 --> 00:07:05,996
Anyway, Elgar and the Jews
don't mix very well.

63
00:07:07,007 --> 00:07:10,091
- I'm not a Jew.
- No, I am.

64
00:07:11,720 --> 00:07:13,250
I wasn't accusing you.

65
00:07:16,558 --> 00:07:19,179
Can I sit in the car 
with my cello?

66
00:07:19,644 --> 00:07:21,103
Jump in.

67
00:07:31,740 --> 00:07:35,073
I've never seen a car like 
this before. C'est très chic.

68
00:07:35,160 --> 00:07:37,034
It's a Bristol. 
Not many of them made.

69
00:07:40,415 --> 00:07:43,701
- Where to, madam?
- I only live round the corner.

70
00:07:44,461 --> 00:07:46,833
- Worse luck.
- I'll see what I can do.

71
00:08:04,189 --> 00:08:06,347
I suppose cellists must go
to a lot of concerts.

72
00:08:06,858 --> 00:08:10,523
We don't go to any concerts.
We don't believe in them.

73
00:08:10,612 --> 00:08:13,862
- They're real.
- So people say.

74
00:08:14,699 --> 00:08:17,024
- Smoke?
- I'd better not.

75
00:08:18,328 --> 00:08:19,787
I live just up there.

76
00:08:24,542 --> 00:08:27,994
- Why don't we believe in them?
- He'd say there's no point to them.

77
00:08:28,171 --> 00:08:30,247
- Your father, this is?
- Yes.

78
00:08:30,924 --> 00:08:32,751
They're just for fun.

79
00:08:32,884 --> 00:08:36,383
Apart from school concerts, which are
no fun at all, so we go to those.

80
00:08:37,388 --> 00:08:39,714
- They don't help you get on.
- Which, of course,

81
00:08:39,808 --> 00:08:41,599
is what's so wonderful about them.

82
00:08:42,393 --> 00:08:45,394
- Anyway, you'll go one day.
- I know. I will.

83
00:08:46,731 --> 00:08:50,100
If I go to university, I'm 
going to read what I want ...

84
00:08:50,193 --> 00:08:52,435
and listen to what I want,

85
00:08:52,529 --> 00:08:56,063
and I'm going to look at paintings
and watch French films ...

86
00:08:56,157 --> 00:08:58,695
and I'm going to talk to people
who know lots about lots.

87
00:09:00,286 --> 00:09:02,326
- Good for you.
- Yes.

88
00:09:02,539 --> 00:09:06,370
- Which university?
- Oxford. If I'm lucky.

89
00:09:08,336 --> 00:09:10,329
Did you go anywhere?

90
00:09:10,421 --> 00:09:12,414
I studied what I believe they 
call "the university of life".

91
00:09:13,091 --> 00:09:15,249
I didn't get a 
very good degree, though.

92
00:09:20,098 --> 00:09:22,719
Well, thank you 
for driving me home.

93
00:09:29,524 --> 00:09:32,193
- Are you all right? Have you got it?
- Yes, it's fine.

94
00:09:35,488 --> 00:09:37,564
- Thank you.
- My pleasure.

95
00:09:45,123 --> 00:09:48,823
♪ Sous le ciel de Paris
marchent des amoureux ♪

96
00:09:58,094 --> 00:10:01,759
♪ Sous le pont de Bercy ♪

97
00:10:01,931 --> 00:10:05,514
♪ Un philosophe assis ♪

98
00:10:05,601 --> 00:10:09,053
♪ Deux musiciens, quelques badauds ♪

99
00:10:09,147 --> 00:10:12,147
♪ Puis les gens par milliers ♪

100
00:10:15,445 --> 00:10:17,354
I don't want to hear
any French singing!

101
00:10:18,531 --> 00:10:21,900
French singing wasn't on the 
syllabus last time I looked!

102
00:10:23,244 --> 00:10:25,201
- Battenberg?
- Thank you.

103
00:10:27,331 --> 00:10:29,158
I actually like the crust.

104
00:10:30,376 --> 00:10:32,452
So where are you applying, Graham?

105
00:10:32,545 --> 00:10:35,830
- I'm not sure yet.
- Well! When will you be sure?

106
00:10:36,549 --> 00:10:39,301
You can't let the grass grow
under your feet, young man.

107
00:10:39,385 --> 00:10:42,303
- I might take a year off.
- What for?

108
00:10:42,889 --> 00:10:46,304
I don't know,
maybe do some travelling.

109
00:10:47,059 --> 00:10:48,518
That sort of thing.

110
00:10:50,271 --> 00:10:51,765
Travelling?

111
00:10:53,316 --> 00:10:55,024
What are you, a Teddy Boy?

112
00:10:56,736 --> 00:10:59,487
You know she's going to Oxford,
don't you?

113
00:10:59,655 --> 00:11:01,447
If we get her Latin up to scratch.

114
00:11:01,699 --> 00:11:05,068
So while she's studying English
at Oxford,

115
00:11:05,161 --> 00:11:06,904
you'll be the wandering Jew.

116
00:11:08,831 --> 00:11:11,500
Mr. Mellor, I'm not a Teddy Boy.

117
00:11:12,918 --> 00:11:16,667
I'm an homme sérieux jeune.

118
00:11:17,652 --> 00:11:19,166
No. Yeah!

119
00:11:20,551 --> 00:11:22,923
I'm a homme jeune sérieux. 
A homme ...

120
00:11:36,359 --> 00:11:38,980
- They're for me.
- Who are they from?

121
00:11:43,783 --> 00:11:46,108
- Gosh. Him.
- What's this?

122
00:11:46,410 --> 00:11:49,447
Jack, I'm afraid Jenny's been sent
some flowers from a chap.

123
00:11:49,538 --> 00:11:51,745
- A chap? What kind of chap?
- He's wishing me luck for tonight.

124
00:11:51,832 --> 00:11:54,502
Is that all he's wishing you?
Where'd he get the money from?

125
00:11:54,585 --> 00:11:57,788
- He earns it, I expect.
- Earns it? Why isn't he at school?

126
00:11:57,880 --> 00:11:59,374
Can we just go?

127
00:11:59,465 --> 00:12:01,292
Otherwise the good luck flowers
will actually be responsible ...

128
00:12:01,383 --> 00:12:04,918
for me actually missing the concert,
which would be ironic, n'est-ce pas?

129
00:12:09,433 --> 00:12:12,636
- I don't ... I don't like it.
- Objection noted. Jenny?

130
00:12:12,728 --> 00:12:14,637
- Noted.
- Yeah, well ...

131
00:12:14,730 --> 00:12:17,268
There's got to be 10 bob's worth
of luck here. I mean ...

132
00:12:17,358 --> 00:12:19,267
That's a bit much for a schoolgirl,
isn't it?

133
00:12:19,401 --> 00:12:20,979
Well, we can't leave it here!

134
00:12:21,237 --> 00:12:23,443
I mean, even I'd burgle a house
with flowers left outside.

135
00:12:23,531 --> 00:12:25,274
They'll think we're made of money.

136
00:12:25,366 --> 00:12:27,192
Thank you, Marjorie.

137
00:12:28,786 --> 00:12:32,653
Camus doesn't want you to like him.
Feeling is bourgeois.

138
00:12:32,748 --> 00:12:35,204
Being engagée is bourgeois.

139
00:12:35,584 --> 00:12:37,956
He kills someone,
and he doesn't feel anything.

140
00:12:38,796 --> 00:12:41,999
His mother dies,
and he doesn't feel anything.

141
00:12:42,758 --> 00:12:44,798
I wouldn't feel anything
if my mother died.

142
00:12:44,885 --> 00:12:46,842
Does that make me 
an existentialist?

143
00:12:46,929 --> 00:12:48,506
No. That makes you a cow.

144
00:12:49,056 --> 00:12:50,598
Une vache.

145
00:12:52,476 --> 00:12:56,889
Well, after I've been to university,
I'm going to be French,

146
00:12:57,106 --> 00:13:02,100
and I'm going to Paris, and I'm 
going to smoke and wear black ...

147
00:13:02,194 --> 00:13:03,688
and listen to Jacques Brel,

148
00:13:03,779 --> 00:13:07,563
and I won't speak, ever.
C'est plus chic comme ça.

149
00:13:08,617 --> 00:13:10,693
- Crikey!
- What?

150
00:13:14,456 --> 00:13:15,832
Wait here.

151
00:13:17,376 --> 00:13:18,870
Hello!

152
00:13:20,379 --> 00:13:21,838
Hello.

153
00:13:24,842 --> 00:13:27,629
Hello.
Thank you.

154
00:13:29,263 --> 00:13:32,679
- How did it go?
- Fine, I think.

155
00:13:33,600 --> 00:13:35,676
I didn't mess my bit up.

156
00:13:36,311 --> 00:13:38,185
Nobody got thrown out
of the orchestra afterwards.

157
00:13:38,313 --> 00:13:41,978
Always the mark of a cultural triumph.
Listen, I'm glad I ran into you.

158
00:13:42,067 --> 00:13:44,439
- What are you doing on Friday?
- Going to school.

159
00:13:44,778 --> 00:13:46,522
I meant in the evening.

160
00:13:46,864 --> 00:13:49,568
Of course. Nothing.

161
00:13:49,658 --> 00:13:53,703
Because I'm going to listen to some
Ravel in St. John's Smith Square.

162
00:13:53,787 --> 00:13:56,823
My friends Danny and Helen would be
coming, too, so it wouldn't be ...

163
00:13:58,959 --> 00:14:01,664
I'll tell you what,
I'll come and pick you up,

164
00:14:01,837 --> 00:14:03,117
and if your mother and father
disapprove,

165
00:14:03,213 --> 00:14:04,873
then you can have the tickets
and go with one of them.

166
00:14:04,965 --> 00:14:06,839
- How does that sound?
- Thank you.

167
00:14:07,259 --> 00:14:10,842
- And I'd like to go with you.
- 7:00?

168
00:14:12,264 --> 00:14:14,007
What are they saying?

169
00:14:14,975 --> 00:14:19,388
And, probably go for
a spot of supper afterwards.

170
00:14:19,479 --> 00:14:21,887
- Supper?
- If you want to.

171
00:14:24,276 --> 00:14:27,692
Well the thing is,
we'll probably have eaten.

172
00:14:27,779 --> 00:14:30,566
Well, if you'd like supper,

173
00:14:30,657 --> 00:14:34,655
then perhaps on Friday
you could not eat?

174
00:14:36,496 --> 00:14:38,619
Yes. Of course.

175
00:14:48,884 --> 00:14:51,209
- A spot of supper?
- You've heard of supper.

176
00:14:51,303 --> 00:14:52,927
We've heard of it,
but we've never eaten it.

177
00:14:53,221 --> 00:14:54,881
So you're going to have
to tell us everything.

178
00:14:54,973 --> 00:14:56,764
Otherwise it's not fair.

179
00:14:57,893 --> 00:15:00,218
- I won't allow it!
- Fine! He's more than happy ...

180
00:15:00,312 --> 00:15:02,269
for you to take me.
- Fine, I will.

181
00:15:02,773 --> 00:15:04,231
- Good!
- Well, where is it?

182
00:15:04,566 --> 00:15:06,144
- St. John's Smith Square.
- Where's that?

183
00:15:06,234 --> 00:15:07,693
I don't know.
I'm sure we could find out.

184
00:15:07,778 --> 00:15:10,315
It's in Westminster.
Right next door to the Abbey.

185
00:15:10,405 --> 00:15:12,528
- How do you know that?
- I had a life ...

186
00:15:12,616 --> 00:15:15,107
before we were married, you know.
You soon put a stop to that.

187
00:15:15,243 --> 00:15:17,236
- Well, there you are.
- Where are we?

188
00:15:17,329 --> 00:15:20,199
We're near Westminster Abbey.
I'm not going all the way over there.

189
00:15:20,290 --> 00:15:22,579
The trouble is that's where
St. John's Smith Square is.

190
00:15:22,667 --> 00:15:25,123
Well, there must be something on
locally. Where's the paper?

191
00:15:25,253 --> 00:15:27,080
She wants to see 
someone who can play.

192
00:15:27,172 --> 00:15:30,707
She doesn't want to see Sheila Kirkland
scratching away. I'll take her.

193
00:15:30,800 --> 00:15:33,338
And how do you propose to 
get there? RAF helicopter?

194
00:15:35,513 --> 00:15:36,794
- That's him.
- Bloody hell!

195
00:15:36,932 --> 00:15:39,683
- Jack!
- By the way, David's a Jew.

196
00:15:39,935 --> 00:15:42,556
A wandering Jew. 
So watch yourself.

197
00:15:44,022 --> 00:15:47,106
What does she mean by that?
I've never said anything like that!

198
00:15:47,275 --> 00:15:50,312
It's just an expression.
I've got nothing against the Jews ...

199
00:15:51,488 --> 00:15:53,480
Glad to hear it. Hello.

200
00:15:54,407 --> 00:15:57,278
I didn't mean I've got nothing against
you. No, of course I do mean that.

201
00:15:57,369 --> 00:16:00,453
- Dad.
- No. It's ... Sorry, it's just that ...

202
00:16:01,831 --> 00:16:05,450
You're not the sort of person
that I would be against.

203
00:16:05,543 --> 00:16:08,995
Well, I wouldn't, because I'm not
the kind of person who would be against ...

204
00:16:10,465 --> 00:16:11,959
people.

205
00:16:13,718 --> 00:16:16,340
I'm Jack. This is my wife, Marjorie.

206
00:16:17,097 --> 00:16:18,923
You didn't tell me
you had a sister, Jenny.

207
00:16:23,353 --> 00:16:25,096
Please.

208
00:16:26,147 --> 00:16:27,855
You're a lucky man, Jack.

209
00:16:29,025 --> 00:16:30,769
Yes, I suppose I am.

210
00:16:39,953 --> 00:16:42,574
- This is lovely.
- Thank you.

211
00:16:43,540 --> 00:16:46,492
I'm sorry, David.
Would you like a drink?

212
00:16:47,001 --> 00:16:49,671
I'd love one, Jack,
but we're running a little late.

213
00:16:50,255 --> 00:16:52,828
If Jenny's ready,
perhaps we'll shoot off?

214
00:16:54,676 --> 00:16:58,294
Actually, David, Dad has 
something he has to tell you.

215
00:16:59,931 --> 00:17:04,676
No, no. Really. Well, it was just
a question, a point of reference.

216
00:17:04,769 --> 00:17:09,431
What's the best way to get to
St. John's Smith Square from here?

217
00:17:09,607 --> 00:17:11,814
It's a straight run, really.
Up to Hammersmith,

218
00:17:11,985 --> 00:17:13,858
take the A4 through Kensington,
you're there.

219
00:17:14,028 --> 00:17:15,902
- As simple as that?
- As simple as that.

220
00:17:16,823 --> 00:17:19,492
- Shall I book us some tickets?
- No.

221
00:17:20,577 --> 00:17:23,281
Well, have her back by 10:00, David.

222
00:17:25,373 --> 00:17:27,081
Well, I was hoping she might 
come with me afterwards ...

223
00:17:27,166 --> 00:17:28,791
for a spot of supper 
with my Aunt Helen.

224
00:17:30,983 --> 00:17:32,129
Well ...

225
00:17:33,172 --> 00:17:35,414
No, no, well ...

226
00:17:35,508 --> 00:17:37,050
She's usually in bed by then.

227
00:17:37,635 --> 00:17:39,711
What if I promise
to have her back by 11:30?

228
00:17:42,307 --> 00:17:44,383
Well, it's Friday night,

229
00:17:45,184 --> 00:17:46,844
and you are going all the way
to the West End.

230
00:17:47,270 --> 00:17:49,595
Thanks, Jack. I appreciate it.

231
00:17:50,106 --> 00:17:51,565
All right.

232
00:17:53,484 --> 00:17:55,062
- Bye.
- Bye-bye.

233
00:17:56,154 --> 00:17:57,897
Have a nice time.

234
00:18:05,288 --> 00:18:07,364
Come on.

235
00:18:12,545 --> 00:18:14,265
Hello, hello!

236
00:18:15,381 --> 00:18:16,460
Are we late?

237
00:18:16,549 --> 00:18:18,292
No, I thought we were going 
to miss the beginning,

238
00:18:18,384 --> 00:18:19,547
and then it wouldn't 
be worth going in ...

239
00:18:19,635 --> 00:18:21,343
and we could all go off dancing
or something.

240
00:18:21,429 --> 00:18:22,888
Helen is one of the more
reluctant members ...

241
00:18:22,972 --> 00:18:24,799
of tonight's audience.
- Hello.

242
00:18:24,891 --> 00:18:28,260
Jenny, these are my friends,
Helen and Danny. Shall we?

243
00:18:28,519 --> 00:18:30,844
- Hello.
- All right?

244
00:18:32,815 --> 00:18:35,140
- 4, please.
- Thank you, sir.

245
00:18:37,945 --> 00:18:39,523
- Sorry.
- That's all right.

246
00:18:39,614 --> 00:18:41,772
- It's lovely, isn't it?
- It's beautiful.

247
00:18:42,241 --> 00:18:46,156
- Where did you get it from?
- I don't know. Chelsea somewhere.

248
00:18:49,207 --> 00:18:53,500
Yours is ... Well, good for
this sort of concert, isn't it?

249
00:18:54,212 --> 00:18:55,706
Thank you.

250
00:18:56,547 --> 00:18:59,038
We should go shopping together 
one day, you and I, if you want.

251
00:18:59,133 --> 00:19:00,711
That would be nice.

252
00:19:01,427 --> 00:19:04,926
But Chelsea,
c'est beaucoup trop cher pour moi.

253
00:19:06,140 --> 00:19:07,682
Sorry?

254
00:19:08,059 --> 00:19:10,846
I just said,
"It's too expensive for me."

255
00:19:11,854 --> 00:19:14,096
No, you didn't. You said 
something completely different.

256
00:19:14,273 --> 00:19:15,732
No, well ...

257
00:19:16,192 --> 00:19:18,730
- I said it in French.
- In French? Why?

258
00:19:20,404 --> 00:19:21,946
I don't know.

259
00:19:23,282 --> 00:19:25,738
Well, Chelsea's too expensive
for me, too, really,

260
00:19:25,826 --> 00:19:27,985
but we don't have 
to worry about that.

261
00:19:28,079 --> 00:19:31,115
If you want something in Chelsea,
just get David to take you shopping.

262
00:19:31,791 --> 00:19:34,032
Why would David want
to take me shopping?

263
00:20:26,011 --> 00:20:28,502
I booked a table at Juliette's.
Will that kill the mood, do you think?

264
00:20:28,806 --> 00:20:33,010
I hope so! God, I always think
I'm going to my own funeral ...

265
00:20:33,102 --> 00:20:35,557
when I listen to classical music.

266
00:20:36,105 --> 00:20:39,141
- That was classical, wasn't it?
- Yes. Very classical.

267
00:20:39,275 --> 00:20:41,314
- As classical as you can get.
- Juliette's it is, then.

268
00:20:41,402 --> 00:20:45,020
Heaven forbid we should end the evening
reflecting on our own mortality.

269
00:20:51,328 --> 00:20:56,239
♪ I want a Sunday kind of love ♪

270
00:20:58,460 --> 00:21:03,917
♪ A love to last past Saturday night ♪

271
00:21:05,259 --> 00:21:09,043
Miles Davis, Sartre ...

272
00:21:09,138 --> 00:21:12,423
Extraordinary woman, Gréco.
Just like you, Helen.

273
00:21:13,600 --> 00:21:16,685
What about Chante Françoise Sagan?
Have you heard that one?

274
00:21:17,813 --> 00:21:19,556
- It's wonderful.
- I've only got ...

275
00:21:19,648 --> 00:21:22,353
I think it's just 
called Juliette Gréco.

276
00:21:22,443 --> 00:21:24,815
The one with the eyes 
on the sleeve? I saved up ...

277
00:21:24,903 --> 00:21:27,608
and got my French Conversation teacher
to bring it back after Christmas.

278
00:21:27,698 --> 00:21:30,367
- You have a French Conversation teacher?
- Yes.

279
00:21:30,451 --> 00:21:33,024
Is that why you suddenly speak 
French for no reason?

280
00:21:34,580 --> 00:21:37,071
Have you never heard her sing?
She's marvellous.

281
00:21:37,207 --> 00:21:38,999
You should see her in Paris,
though, not here.

282
00:21:39,418 --> 00:21:41,245
David will take you.

283
00:21:42,546 --> 00:21:46,413
- I'd love to. You'd fit right in.
- Better than here, really.

284
00:21:46,508 --> 00:21:48,631
Isn't it wonderful
to find a young person ...

285
00:21:48,719 --> 00:21:51,755
who wants to know things?
There's so much I want you to see.

286
00:21:57,853 --> 00:21:58,884
Are you all right
to come and have a look ...

287
00:21:58,979 --> 00:22:01,137
at that Pembroke Villas place 
with me on Friday, Danny?

288
00:22:01,440 --> 00:22:05,307
No, I can't. There's a Burne-Jones
coming up at Christie's on Friday.

289
00:22:05,485 --> 00:22:06,861
Desperate to get my hands on it.

290
00:22:06,945 --> 00:22:08,653
You're thinking of 
buying a Burne-Jones?

291
00:22:09,260 --> 00:22:10,612
A real one?

292
00:22:11,450 --> 00:22:13,608
I just have a feeling the
Pre-Raphaelites are going to take off.

293
00:22:13,702 --> 00:22:15,493
I love the Pre-Raphaelites!

294
00:22:15,704 --> 00:22:17,697
- Do you?
- Yes, of course!

295
00:22:17,956 --> 00:22:20,198
Rossetti and Burne-Jones, anyway.
Not Holman Hunt so much,

296
00:22:20,292 --> 00:22:22,368
he's so garish.
- Absolutely.

297
00:22:24,004 --> 00:22:25,831
Well, why don't we all go
to the auction together?

298
00:22:25,922 --> 00:22:29,541
- Auction! Gosh, how exciting.
- It's Friday morning.

299
00:22:32,929 --> 00:22:34,182
Friday.

300
00:22:35,766 --> 00:22:39,514
- You're busy?
- Well, yes.

301
00:22:39,686 --> 00:22:41,228
Tant pis.

302
00:22:41,396 --> 00:22:43,721
Quel dommage.
C'est pas de problème. C'est ...

303
00:22:45,317 --> 00:22:49,860
- Are you sure you're busy?
- No. I'm sure I could rearrange.

304
00:22:51,114 --> 00:22:52,656
That would be lovely.

305
00:23:10,008 --> 00:23:14,385
♪ You got me wrapped around your ♪

306
00:23:14,471 --> 00:23:17,425
♪ little finger ♪

307
00:23:17,766 --> 00:23:20,091
♪ If this is love ♪

308
00:23:21,394 --> 00:23:26,899
♪ It's everything I hoped it would be ♪

309
00:23:31,905 --> 00:23:34,230
♪ When we kiss ♪

310
00:23:35,492 --> 00:23:37,650
♪ It's as if ♪

311
00:23:39,120 --> 00:23:41,991
♪ Our lips agree ♪

312
00:23:42,999 --> 00:23:48,539
♪ That we were meant to be ♪

313
00:23:53,510 --> 00:23:55,337
♪ When we touch ... ♪

314
00:24:08,066 --> 00:24:11,850
- What are you doing?
- I can't get this casserole dish clean,

315
00:24:11,945 --> 00:24:13,569
it's all burned around the ...

316
00:24:14,072 --> 00:24:15,566
It's 25 to 12:00.

317
00:24:18,159 --> 00:24:21,493
- We finished tea at 7:00.
- I know what time it is.

318
00:24:22,831 --> 00:24:24,325
How was your evening?

319
00:24:25,625 --> 00:24:27,582
Best night of my life.

320
00:24:35,844 --> 00:24:37,338
Night, Mum.

321
00:24:43,268 --> 00:24:49,187
I think there were 1 violins,
1 cello, 2 violas, a harp ...

322
00:24:49,274 --> 00:24:50,851
I don't want to hear about Ravel.

323
00:24:50,942 --> 00:24:52,769
I want to know
what else was on the programme.

324
00:24:52,944 --> 00:24:55,400
It was nothing like that.
He was a perfect gentleman.

325
00:24:55,488 --> 00:24:57,777
He just said he wanted to take 
me places and show me things.

326
00:24:57,866 --> 00:25:00,321
- "Things"?
- Plural? My God!

327
00:25:01,161 --> 00:25:03,948
I knew that Jane Eyre would
eventually work its magic on you.

328
00:25:04,080 --> 00:25:06,322
I'm assuming that's what 
you're all so animated about.

329
00:25:06,416 --> 00:25:08,159
- Of course.
- Jane Eyre ...

330
00:25:08,251 --> 00:25:10,956
and Jenny's new boyfriend.
- He's not my new boyfriend.

331
00:25:11,254 --> 00:25:13,045
That's true. He's more 
of a man friend, actually.

332
00:25:13,131 --> 00:25:16,167
- He's got a sports car, Miss Stubbs!
- It's maroon.

333
00:25:16,259 --> 00:25:18,880
So could we call him
a Mr. Rochester figure?

334
00:25:19,012 --> 00:25:21,633
I think he must be as blind
as Mr. Rochester.

335
00:25:22,390 --> 00:25:24,513
You may or may not have noticed I'm 
trying to steer the subject away ...

336
00:25:24,601 --> 00:25:26,973
from Jenny's lurid love life
into the matter in hand.

337
00:25:27,604 --> 00:25:28,979
And it is clear from this evidence ...

338
00:25:29,063 --> 00:25:30,807
that most of you know far too 
much about the former ...

339
00:25:30,898 --> 00:25:32,606
and next to nothing 
about the latter.

340
00:25:33,151 --> 00:25:36,602
Reluctantly, I have to admit that 
Jenny is clearly an expert on both.

341
00:25:36,904 --> 00:25:39,063
Excellent as always, Jenny.

342
00:25:52,253 --> 00:25:53,579
Hello.

343
00:25:54,088 --> 00:25:55,666
Hello.

344
00:26:13,274 --> 00:26:15,148
Any further bids?

345
00:26:15,902 --> 00:26:18,274
- Sold, then, for 60 guineas.
- Hello.

346
00:26:19,238 --> 00:26:20,898
You're late.

347
00:26:21,699 --> 00:26:25,198
We now turn to Lot 41.

348
00:26:25,286 --> 00:26:28,702
The Tree of Forgiveness
by Sir Edward Burne-Jones.

349
00:26:28,831 --> 00:26:33,873
This is a rare opportunity to purchase a
key work of the Pre-Raphaelite movement.

350
00:26:34,128 --> 00:26:37,046
- Who will start me off at 100 guineas?
- Is it that one?

351
00:26:37,131 --> 00:26:38,756
Yes, that's the one.

352
00:26:39,383 --> 00:26:41,257
15 guineas?

353
00:26:42,428 --> 00:26:43,970
20 guineas?

354
00:26:44,597 --> 00:26:48,595
Thank you. 40? Thank you, sir.

355
00:26:48,976 --> 00:26:50,720
Do I hear 60?

356
00:26:51,395 --> 00:26:54,599
80 guineas? Thank you, sir.

357
00:26:54,690 --> 00:26:56,730
Another one, madam? 100 guineas?

358
00:26:57,360 --> 00:26:58,902
120?

359
00:27:02,990 --> 00:27:04,734
No further bids?

360
00:27:05,451 --> 00:27:06,862
- Your turn.
- What?

361
00:27:06,953 --> 00:27:08,613
- Any further bids?
- Your turn.

362
00:27:09,413 --> 00:27:10,742
- Any more?
- Quick!

363
00:27:10,831 --> 00:27:13,868
120 guineas from the
very eager new bidder.

364
00:27:14,043 --> 00:27:15,621
140, madam?

365
00:27:16,170 --> 00:27:18,922
Thank you. 160 guineas?

366
00:27:19,590 --> 00:27:21,998
180? Thank you.

367
00:27:22,802 --> 00:27:24,296
200 guineas?

368
00:27:25,346 --> 00:27:27,054
220?

369
00:27:29,308 --> 00:27:30,767
Another one, madam?

370
00:27:36,649 --> 00:27:40,232
Sold for 200 guineas. Thank you.

371
00:27:41,362 --> 00:27:44,031
- Your name, please?
- Mellor.

372
00:27:46,909 --> 00:27:49,365
Now we move on to Lot 42 ...

373
00:27:49,453 --> 00:27:51,944
Thank you very much. I couldn't 
possibly have bought it without you.

374
00:27:54,083 --> 00:27:55,162
Just a couple of years ago,

375
00:27:55,251 --> 00:27:57,955
you could pick one of them up 
for 50 quid. No one was interested.

376
00:27:58,087 --> 00:28:00,329
I would have been so interested.

377
00:28:01,632 --> 00:28:04,301
As you can see, I just love things.

378
00:28:08,305 --> 00:28:10,381
That's not a Lockey-Hill!

379
00:28:11,725 --> 00:28:13,350
There aren't many people
who come in here and say that.

380
00:28:13,435 --> 00:28:14,550
No, certainly not me.

381
00:28:14,958 --> 00:28:17,562
- It's beautiful! Do you play?
- Thank you.

382
00:28:17,648 --> 00:28:20,435
I used to. I vowed to myself
that one day I'd own one of these ...

383
00:28:20,526 --> 00:28:22,353
and now I do own one,
I don't touch the bugger.

384
00:28:22,486 --> 00:28:25,060
It's vulgar, really,
putting it on display.

385
00:28:25,155 --> 00:28:26,650
Give it to Jenny.

386
00:28:27,366 --> 00:28:30,201
- I think that would be even more vulgar.
- Play for us, Jenny.

387
00:28:30,286 --> 00:28:34,153
- No, one day, when I'm good enough.
- She's good enough now.

388
00:28:34,248 --> 00:28:36,537
David, you've never seen me play.

389
00:28:37,209 --> 00:28:39,831
I can come and hear you in Oxford,
when you get there.

390
00:28:40,004 --> 00:28:41,747
We should all go
and spend a weekend in Oxford.

391
00:28:42,256 --> 00:28:45,043
Straw boaters, 
punting, cream teas ...

392
00:28:45,134 --> 00:28:47,340
- Boats.
... antiquarian book shops.

393
00:28:47,928 --> 00:28:49,506
Bit of business, if we can find it.

394
00:28:49,597 --> 00:28:51,172
What about next weekend?

395
00:28:52,725 --> 00:28:54,183
Yes.

396
00:28:54,601 --> 00:28:56,060
I wouldn't be allowed to do that.

397
00:28:59,481 --> 00:29:02,435
- I'll talk to them.
- You're going to ask my father ...

398
00:29:02,526 --> 00:29:04,649
if you can take me 
away for the weekend?

399
00:29:04,737 --> 00:29:07,062
- He'd have you arrested.
- We'll see.

400
00:29:08,657 --> 00:29:10,449
- I bet you can't.
- How much?

401
00:29:10,534 --> 00:29:14,033
I'd be careful if I were you, Jenny.
You don't know who you're dealing with.

402
00:29:14,413 --> 00:29:15,872
Half a crown.

403
00:29:16,665 --> 00:29:18,124
You're on.

404
00:29:20,753 --> 00:29:22,247
How do you know Danny?

405
00:29:22,337 --> 00:29:26,501
You know.
We kept bumping into each other,

406
00:29:26,592 --> 00:29:28,335
then we became pals,

407
00:29:29,344 --> 00:29:31,966
and we've ended up doing a bit
of business together when it suits us.

408
00:29:32,055 --> 00:29:35,721
- What kind of business?
- Property, a bit of art dealing.

409
00:29:37,603 --> 00:29:40,438
Some buying and selling. 
This and that.

410
00:29:48,238 --> 00:29:51,441
- Right. I'll just be 2 ticks.
- Okay.

411
00:30:00,959 --> 00:30:05,538
- Mr. Goldman, good to see you.
- Jolly good. Madam.

412
00:30:06,465 --> 00:30:07,959
All right.

413
00:30:12,596 --> 00:30:15,965
- All right, I've got this one. And ...
- Put me down!

414
00:30:18,477 --> 00:30:19,935
Go on, then.

415
00:30:59,976 --> 00:31:01,636
Sorry about that.

416
00:31:03,688 --> 00:31:06,014
How do you know those negro people?

417
00:31:06,108 --> 00:31:08,433
- They're clients.
- Clients?

418
00:31:09,986 --> 00:31:11,896
Schvartzers have to live somewhere.

419
00:31:11,988 --> 00:31:14,740
It's not as if they can rent
off their own kind, is it?

420
00:31:20,997 --> 00:31:26,074
Test results for the Virgil translation.
We'll start from the bottom.

421
00:31:26,670 --> 00:31:28,413
Patricia.

422
00:31:28,588 --> 00:31:30,130
Absent.

423
00:31:30,465 --> 00:31:34,214
Margaret, 48%.

424
00:31:35,470 --> 00:31:37,012
Jenny!

425
00:31:37,931 --> 00:31:40,967
52%.

426
00:31:41,643 --> 00:31:45,771
That would just about scrape 
a pass in the exam proper.

427
00:31:45,855 --> 00:31:48,856
Not good enough 
for Oxford candidates.

428
00:31:54,573 --> 00:31:58,570
- It's her Latin, isn't it?
- Everyone's doing their best, Jack.

429
00:31:59,452 --> 00:32:02,660
But what if everyone's best isn't 
good enough? What do we do then?

430
00:32:04,374 --> 00:32:06,367
Well, perhaps the whole thing's
been a waste of money, anyway.

431
00:32:06,459 --> 00:32:08,535
- You don't mean that.
- Well, what's she going to do ...

432
00:32:08,628 --> 00:32:10,170
with an English degree?

433
00:32:10,255 --> 00:32:13,090
If she's going to spend 3 years
playing that bloody cello,

434
00:32:13,174 --> 00:32:15,547
talking in French
to a bunch of beatniks,

435
00:32:15,635 --> 00:32:18,672
well, I'm just throwing
good money after bad.

436
00:32:18,763 --> 00:32:20,305
Well, she might meet
a nice lawyer there,

437
00:32:20,390 --> 00:32:22,762
but she could do that
at a dinner dance tomorrow!

438
00:32:22,851 --> 00:32:25,970
Because that's the point of
an Oxford education, isn't it, Dad?

439
00:32:26,062 --> 00:32:28,518
It's the expensive alternative
to a dinner dance.

440
00:32:29,024 --> 00:32:30,815
What about private tuition?

441
00:32:32,193 --> 00:32:35,360
Can anybody hear me?
How much is this going to cost me?

442
00:32:35,447 --> 00:32:37,985
5 shillings an hour,
maybe a little more for A-level.

443
00:32:38,074 --> 00:32:41,028
5 bob? We spend 5 bob here,
we spend five bob there.

444
00:32:41,119 --> 00:32:42,779
Next thing you know,
that's our savings down the drain.

445
00:32:42,871 --> 00:32:44,579
And what else
are we spending 5 bob on?

446
00:32:44,664 --> 00:32:46,372
What else are we 
spending sixpence on?

447
00:32:46,499 --> 00:32:50,711
Nothing! No! Nothing. All of 
this is free. This vase is free.

448
00:32:50,795 --> 00:32:52,788
It was, actually.
It was a present from Auntie Vi.

449
00:32:52,881 --> 00:32:56,830
That chair, this sofa, it's all free.
We didn't have to pay for any of it.

450
00:32:56,926 --> 00:32:59,464
You see,
that's the beauty of life, Jenny.

451
00:32:59,554 --> 00:33:01,297
You don't have to pay for anything.

452
00:33:01,473 --> 00:33:04,390
You know, there's a lovely Oxford 
tree growing in the garden.

453
00:33:04,475 --> 00:33:06,967
Lucky for you, because that's 
Oxford taken care of.

454
00:33:07,103 --> 00:33:10,768
And there's a whole orchard of 
school trees, so that school is free,

455
00:33:10,940 --> 00:33:13,431
and I think there's even
a private tuition tree in there.

456
00:33:13,526 --> 00:33:15,353
- I'll just go and check, shall I?
- Jack!

457
00:33:15,445 --> 00:33:17,603
It's all right, Marjorie.
Don't worry, I'll only be a second,

458
00:33:17,697 --> 00:33:21,481
because I think there's a whole clump of
them surrounding the pocket money tree!

459
00:33:21,659 --> 00:33:23,948
I'll just go and make sure
they're all nice and safe, shall I?

460
00:33:24,037 --> 00:33:25,412
And by the way, 
you might be lucky.

461
00:33:25,496 --> 00:33:28,332
There might be a man with deep 
pockets growing out there,

462
00:33:28,416 --> 00:33:30,325
because God knows
you're going to need one!

463
00:33:37,342 --> 00:33:39,833
Well, you can always go to 
secretarial college with Hattie.

464
00:33:39,927 --> 00:33:42,086
- Thanks.
- Charming!

465
00:33:43,806 --> 00:33:46,179
- God. No.
- Hello!

466
00:33:47,101 --> 00:33:49,094
Hello, Graham.

467
00:33:50,396 --> 00:33:51,938
I haven't seen you in ages.

468
00:33:56,652 --> 00:34:00,021
It went a bit wrong, didn't it?
The tea party, I mean.

469
00:34:05,286 --> 00:34:07,777
Was it because of the year 
off thing? Because I ...

470
00:34:07,872 --> 00:34:09,366
No!

471
00:34:10,375 --> 00:34:14,835
I just have so much work to do if 
I'm going to get the grades I need.

472
00:34:15,338 --> 00:34:18,007
Yeah, she doesn't 
have time for boys.

473
00:34:26,140 --> 00:34:27,718
- Bye, Graham!
