travelled further than you intended.

714
00:53:10,803 --> 00:53:12,261
Come.

715
00:53:14,682 --> 00:53:16,176
Miss Mellor.

716
00:53:19,978 --> 00:53:23,679
We're all very excited
about your forthcoming trip to Paris.

717
00:53:25,025 --> 00:53:29,983
Our excitement, indeed, knows no bounds.
Some of us can talk of little else.

718
00:53:31,323 --> 00:53:33,565
An older man, I understand?

719
00:53:35,285 --> 00:53:37,693
A word of warning, Miss Mellor.

720
00:53:39,456 --> 00:53:44,332
There may well have been the odd 
6th-form girl who has lost ...

721
00:53:45,629 --> 00:53:48,167
an important part of herself,
perhaps the best part,

722
00:53:48,298 --> 00:53:50,587
while under our supervision.
These things happen, regrettably.

723
00:53:50,676 --> 00:53:52,503
If, however,
we are made aware of that loss,

724
00:53:52,594 --> 00:53:54,670
then of course
the young lady in question ...

725
00:53:54,763 --> 00:53:56,423
would have to continue
her studies elsewhere.

726
00:53:56,515 --> 00:53:58,840
If, that is, she still 
has any use for A-levels.

727
00:53:59,309 --> 00:54:01,266
Do I make myself clear?

728
00:54:03,814 --> 00:54:06,020
- Can I go now?
- If you would.

729
00:54:16,743 --> 00:54:18,535
What are you doing in there?

730
00:54:18,996 --> 00:54:21,403
Well, I imagine she's lighting 
the candles on my cake.

731
00:54:21,790 --> 00:54:23,699
You're 17, not 250.

732
00:54:27,546 --> 00:54:30,666
- Thanks for inviting me.
- It was Marjorie's idea, not mine.

733
00:54:33,302 --> 00:54:35,259
- Not even Jenny's, for that matter.
- Dad!

734
00:54:35,345 --> 00:54:36,626
Ta-da!

735
00:54:39,725 --> 00:54:41,764
Well, blow them out before
the house burns down.

736
00:54:42,394 --> 00:54:45,561
- Make a ... Okay, just ... Don't wait.
- Bravo.

737
00:54:50,569 --> 00:54:51,600
Who'd like a piece?

738
00:54:51,695 --> 00:54:53,522
- Me, please.
- Well, come on, come on. Presents.

739
00:54:54,698 --> 00:54:56,157
It doesn't matter, I'll ...

740
00:55:01,496 --> 00:55:02,872
It's a new Latin dictionary.

741
00:55:07,127 --> 00:55:09,618
Thank you. I needed a new one.

742
00:55:11,256 --> 00:55:14,257
Dear! Got a ... Snap!

743
00:55:27,689 --> 00:55:30,939
Good grief!
Jenny, you should see this!

744
00:55:31,026 --> 00:55:33,232
- It's a special day.
- She's a special girl!

745
00:55:33,320 --> 00:55:34,814
I know it.

746
00:55:37,407 --> 00:55:38,735
Bit of help!

747
00:55:38,825 --> 00:55:40,901
Makes your dictionary look
a bit feeble, Graham?

748
00:55:40,994 --> 00:55:43,200
- Gosh!
- And these are for you.

749
00:55:43,288 --> 00:55:45,957
- Hello, young man.
- David!

750
00:55:46,041 --> 00:55:48,448
- David, would you like a drink?
- I'd love one.

751
00:55:49,169 --> 00:55:53,712
I'd best be going, 'cause I've got
a stack of homework to do, so ...

752
00:55:54,424 --> 00:55:55,835
Well ...

753
00:55:55,926 --> 00:55:58,251
- Thank you. Bye.
- Cheers.

754
00:55:59,012 --> 00:56:01,005
- Bye, Mr. Mellor.
- Cheerio, Graham.

755
00:56:01,097 --> 00:56:02,640
Thank you.

756
00:56:03,183 --> 00:56:05,259
Wonderful to see you, Graham.

757
00:56:06,603 --> 00:56:08,595
- Goodbye, Jenny.
- Bye, Graham.

758
00:56:11,858 --> 00:56:14,431
- A little something warming?
- You know me so well.

759
00:56:14,527 --> 00:56:16,437
- Can I open anything yet?
- Wait for me.

760
00:56:16,529 --> 00:56:19,566
Before you open that lot, I've 
got a surprise. Next weekend,

761
00:56:19,658 --> 00:56:22,861
we're all going to Café de Flore
to celebrate Jenny's birthday.

762
00:56:23,370 --> 00:56:25,906
- Lovely!
- Café de Flore ...

763
00:56:26,122 --> 00:56:28,874
is in the Boulevard St. Germain,
in Paris.

764
00:56:30,126 --> 00:56:32,664
- What do you mean, Paris?
- You know the one, Dad.

765
00:56:34,798 --> 00:56:36,589
No, no. No, no, no.

766
00:56:37,509 --> 00:56:39,548
No, we don't have 
any French money.

767
00:56:39,636 --> 00:56:41,510
And besides, it's too ...

768
00:56:42,222 --> 00:56:44,131
Well, I don't think
it would agree with me.

769
00:56:44,391 --> 00:56:46,549
- Dad!
- The French don't like us, Jenny,

770
00:56:46,643 --> 00:56:49,679
you know that. John Sutton, from 
work, he went there last year.

771
00:56:49,771 --> 00:56:53,056
They were very rude to him.
I don't want to spoil anyone's fun,

772
00:56:53,608 --> 00:56:55,766
but it's just not for me, Europe.

773
00:56:56,694 --> 00:56:59,898
- You'll have to go another time.
- You've just said you don't like Europe.

774
00:56:59,989 --> 00:57:02,065
So what's going to change?
It'll have to be Europe, won't it,

775
00:57:02,158 --> 00:57:04,732
because it certainly won't be you.
- I'll take her.

776
00:57:04,828 --> 00:57:06,488
- To the continent?
- Why not?

777
00:57:06,746 --> 00:57:09,320
- And leave me here on my own?
- For God's sake!

778
00:57:19,342 --> 00:57:20,801
What do you think?

779
00:57:23,096 --> 00:57:25,468
You know what Jenny's like
about France, Jack.

780
00:57:25,932 --> 00:57:29,467
- French films and books and music.
- Of course I do.

781
00:57:29,561 --> 00:57:32,597
Sorry, yes. It goes without 
saying. She's your daughter.

782
00:57:36,818 --> 00:57:38,775
Jenny likes to joke about how 
you're a stick-in-the-mud ...

783
00:57:38,861 --> 00:57:42,028
and all the rest of it,
but I know that's not who you are.

784
00:57:42,949 --> 00:57:45,440
Otherwise, she wouldn't 
be who she is.

785
00:57:46,911 --> 00:57:48,074
No.

786
00:57:48,162 --> 00:57:50,998
But I can also see
that I have acted out of turn,

787
00:57:51,082 --> 00:57:53,573
and I'm sorry.

788
00:58:06,597 --> 00:58:08,555
What about your Aunt Helen?

789
00:58:16,983 --> 00:58:20,518
- An hour late.
- We'll make it. I promise.

790
00:58:22,113 --> 00:58:24,438
Okay, there's a flight
at 8:00 in the morning.

791
00:58:24,741 --> 00:58:26,283
Good.

792
00:58:37,795 --> 00:58:39,587
There's no bed.

793
00:58:39,672 --> 00:58:41,961
I pushed the boat out
and got us a suite.

794
00:58:42,383 --> 00:58:44,091
- A suite?
- Yeah.

795
00:58:44,802 --> 00:58:47,127
Well, if work stops us from 
getting to Paris until tomorrow,

796
00:58:47,221 --> 00:58:50,056
then work can buy 
us a nice hotel room.

797
00:58:51,225 --> 00:58:53,930
Anyway, it's a special occasion,
isn't it?

798
00:58:54,478 --> 00:58:57,563
I'd have thought tonight, of 
all nights, we'd only need a bed.

799
00:59:15,166 --> 00:59:18,286
Hold on, one second. 
I've got something.

800
00:59:31,265 --> 00:59:32,843
I thought ...

801
00:59:32,933 --> 00:59:34,891
I thought we might 
practise with this.

802
00:59:36,187 --> 00:59:37,597
With a banana?

803
00:59:37,688 --> 00:59:40,358
I thought we might get the 
messy bit over with first.

804
00:59:41,400 --> 00:59:42,859
What?

805
00:59:43,778 --> 00:59:45,236
David!

806
00:59:45,529 --> 00:59:48,400
I don't want to lose my virginity
to a piece of fruit!

807
00:59:50,868 --> 00:59:52,410
I'm sorry.

808
00:59:55,247 --> 00:59:56,623
Hey.

809
00:59:59,502 --> 01:00:01,827
- I think the moment might have gone.
- Hey, hey ...

810
01:00:01,921 --> 01:00:05,100
- I think we should wait until Paris.
- I'm sorry ...

811
01:00:06,217 --> 01:00:07,675
Minnie, I ...

812
01:00:10,304 --> 01:00:12,510
I'm an idiot. I'm sorry.

813
01:00:13,933 --> 01:00:15,391
David,

814
01:00:15,768 --> 01:00:19,303
if tomorrow night does happen,
it's only ever going to happen once.

815
01:00:19,980 --> 01:00:22,650
Why will it only ever happen once?

816
01:00:23,025 --> 01:00:24,934
Because the first time
can only ever happen once.

817
01:00:26,987 --> 01:00:30,237
So ...no baby talk.

818
01:00:31,659 --> 01:00:33,201
No Minnie.

819
01:00:38,874 --> 01:00:42,409
Just treat me like a grown-up.

820
01:00:43,963 --> 01:00:45,457
Okay?

821
01:00:51,887 --> 01:00:55,054
I know. Let's go and sit 
in our sitting room.

822
01:00:56,267 --> 01:00:57,725
All right.

823
01:00:58,936 --> 01:01:00,513
We'll order up some champagne.

824
01:01:12,157 --> 01:01:13,616
Room service?

825
01:01:15,202 --> 01:01:22,450
♪ Quand doucement tu te penches
En murmurant, "C'est dimanche" ♪

826
01:01:23,335 --> 01:01:27,167
♪ Si nous allions en banlieue
faire un tour ♪

827
01:01:27,256 --> 01:01:30,340
♪ Sous le ciel bleu des beaux jours? ♪

828
01:01:31,135 --> 01:01:34,504
♪ Mille projets nous attirent ♪

829
01:01:35,055 --> 01:01:38,139
♪ Mais dans un même sourire ♪

830
01:01:39,017 --> 01:01:42,932
♪ Nous refaisons le trajet
simple et doux ♪

831
01:01:43,021 --> 01:01:47,315
♪ De nos premiers rendez-vous ♪

832
01:01:47,860 --> 01:01:53,483
♪ Sur les quais du vieux Paris ♪

833
01:01:53,574 --> 01:01:57,406
♪ Le long de la Seine, 
le bonheur sourit ♪

834
01:01:58,328 --> 01:02:02,575
♪ Sur les quais du vieux Paris ♪

835
01:02:02,666 --> 01:02:07,375
♪ L'amour se promène 
en cherchant un nid ♪

836
