♪ Vieux bouquiniste Belle fleuriste ♪

837
01:02:12,968 --> 01:02:17,131
♪ Comme on vous aime Vivant poème ♪

838
01:02:17,973 --> 01:02:22,931
♪ Sur les quais du vieux Paris ... ♪

839
01:02:23,020 --> 01:02:26,720
♪ De I'amour bohème ♪

840
01:02:27,065 --> 01:02:29,437
♪ C'est le paradis ♪

841
01:02:42,956 --> 01:02:45,163
Do you still feel 
like a schoolgirl?

842
01:02:51,882 --> 01:02:54,124
It wasn't too uncomfortable?

843
01:02:54,593 --> 01:02:57,166
Not after the first bit.

844
01:02:59,639 --> 01:03:01,881
It's funny, though, isn't it?

845
01:03:05,353 --> 01:03:08,473
All that poetry 
and all those songs ...

846
01:03:09,608 --> 01:03:11,399
about something
that lasts no time at all.

847
01:03:13,820 --> 01:03:15,314
Yeah.

848
01:03:17,741 --> 01:03:21,110
All your exercise books on 
my desk in a pile, please.

849
01:03:24,039 --> 01:03:26,031
I bought this for you.

850
01:03:30,962 --> 01:03:33,038
That's very kind of you.

851
01:03:36,468 --> 01:03:37,962
But I can't accept it.

852
01:03:39,513 --> 01:03:40,971
Why not?

853
01:03:42,516 --> 01:03:43,761
It's because of people like you ...

854
01:03:43,850 --> 01:03:47,718
that I plough through illiterate essays
by Sandra Lovell about her pony.

855
01:03:49,773 --> 01:03:52,061
But I know where 
this came from, Jenny,

856
01:03:52,817 --> 01:03:57,361
and if I took it, I feel
I would be betraying both of us.

857
01:04:12,420 --> 01:04:13,879
Jenny?

858
01:04:17,509 --> 01:04:20,213
You can do anything you want.
You know that.

859
01:04:21,304 --> 01:04:23,760
You're clever, and you're pretty.

860
01:04:27,102 --> 01:04:30,221
Is your boyfriend interested
in clever, Jenny?

861
01:04:32,065 --> 01:04:33,974
I'm not quite sure
what you're trying to tell me.

862
01:04:34,067 --> 01:04:37,317
I'm telling you to go to Oxford,
no matter what.

863
01:04:39,072 --> 01:04:41,563
Because if you don't,
you'll break my heart.

864
01:04:48,832 --> 01:04:51,702
- Where did you go?
- Cambridge.

865
01:04:52,335 --> 01:04:56,664
Well, you're clever and you're pretty,
so presumably clever Miss Stubbs won ...

866
01:04:56,756 --> 01:04:58,464
and here you are with your pony essays.

867
01:04:59,551 --> 01:05:02,754
I don't know, these last few months,
I've eaten in wonderful restaurants ...

868
01:05:02,846 --> 01:05:07,970
and been to jazz clubs and watched
wonderful films, heard beautiful music.

869
01:05:10,270 --> 01:05:13,224
- Jenny, are you taking precautions?
- It's nothing to do with that.

870
01:05:14,190 --> 01:05:16,099
- Isn't it?
- Maybe all our lives are going to end up ...

871
01:05:16,192 --> 01:05:18,564
with pony essays, or housework.

872
01:05:19,612 --> 01:05:21,237
And, yes, 
maybe we'll go to Oxford,

873
01:05:21,322 --> 01:05:22,817
but if we're all going to die
the moment we graduate,

874
01:05:22,907 --> 01:05:25,232
isn't it what we 
do before that counts?

875
01:05:30,832 --> 01:05:32,623
I'm sorry you think I'm dead.

876
01:05:35,378 --> 01:05:37,038
I don't think you're dead,
I just don't ...

877
01:05:37,130 --> 01:05:39,087
I think you'd better go
to your next class.

878
01:05:53,479 --> 01:05:54,938
Go, go, go!

879
01:05:57,942 --> 01:05:59,602
Well done, Jenny!

880
01:05:59,694 --> 01:06:02,267
I've never won anything before, not 
even at the Women's Institute raffle.

881
01:06:02,363 --> 01:06:04,652
And I always bet on the sweetest 
looking one and he always comes last.

882
01:06:04,741 --> 01:06:06,567
- Let's go. Come on.
- Can we do it again? I'm feeling lucky.

883
01:06:06,784 --> 01:06:08,362
Come on, let's go,
I don't want to miss him.

884
01:06:08,453 --> 01:06:11,822
- Pick up your 10 bob on the way out.
- I won 10 shillings!

885
01:06:12,206 --> 01:06:16,038
- Who is this man, anyway?
- Peter Rachman. Complete bastard.

886
01:06:16,878 --> 01:06:19,119
Well, why do we have to see him here?

887
01:06:19,213 --> 01:06:21,420
Because he's not the sort 
of chap with an office.

888
01:06:25,386 --> 01:06:27,094
All right.

889
01:06:28,139 --> 01:06:29,633
Ladies.

890
01:06:37,607 --> 01:06:39,683
A bottle of your 
finest champagne, please.

891
01:06:40,193 --> 01:06:41,651
There he is.

892
01:06:46,449 --> 01:06:48,940
Come on, Jenny, tell them
your good news. Don't be bashful.

893
01:06:49,035 --> 01:06:50,778
No, be Sneezy!

894
01:06:51,412 --> 01:06:53,903
Jenny got 2 As and a B
in her mock A-levels.

895
01:06:53,998 --> 01:06:56,204
Like everyone else in this 
sophisticated establishment.

896
01:06:56,292 --> 01:06:59,209
- The B was in Latin.
- Seriously, congratulations.

897
01:06:59,295 --> 01:07:00,754
Excuse us.

898
01:07:06,302 --> 01:07:07,926
Don't worry too much.

899
01:07:09,263 --> 01:07:10,805
About what?

900
01:07:11,140 --> 01:07:14,639
Someone told me that in about 50 years,
no one will speak Latin, probably.

901
01:07:14,727 --> 01:07:17,763
Not even Latin people.
So don't worry about your B.

902
01:07:24,278 --> 01:07:26,187
He's even more of a bastard
than I thought.

903
01:07:26,280 --> 01:07:28,273
You wouldn't want him
to marry your sister.

904
01:07:28,366 --> 01:07:31,153
You wouldn't want to talk to him
in a club, come to that.

905
01:07:32,119 --> 01:07:35,868
You do know what you're doing,
old chap? With Jenny?

906
01:07:36,415 --> 01:07:38,408
- This is the one, Danny.
- Right.

907
01:07:39,210 --> 01:07:40,953
That's it!

908
01:07:41,962 --> 01:07:46,126
- You can see she's different.
- I just don't want to see her hurt.

909
01:08:12,493 --> 01:08:14,782
Have you bought
any more paintings recently?

910
01:08:14,870 --> 01:08:20,410
Have I? Yes! Picked up a 
little Piper. Good one, I think.

911
01:08:20,584 --> 01:08:23,787
I'm still trying to work out what makes
good things good. It's hard, isn't it?

912
01:08:23,879 --> 01:08:26,714
Well, the thing is, Jenny, you know.

913
01:08:27,758 --> 01:08:29,917
Without necessarily being able
to explain why.

914
01:08:30,135 --> 01:08:34,429
See, you have taste.
That's not half the battle.

915
01:08:35,683 --> 01:08:37,141
That's the whole war.

916
01:08:58,998 --> 01:09:01,370
Jenny, we should go. It's late.

917
01:09:01,458 --> 01:09:02,787
- Really?
- Yes.

918
01:09:02,876 --> 01:09:05,546
Alas. One day school
will be over forever ...

919
01:09:05,629 --> 01:09:07,622
and we can talk 
about art all night.

920
01:09:07,715 --> 01:09:12,008
- You're all right in a taxi, aren't you?
- Yeah. Yeah, I'm fine.

921
01:09:12,094 --> 01:09:13,837
Let's go. Come on.

922
01:09:15,472 --> 01:09:17,050
Good night.

923
01:09:23,689 --> 01:09:25,183
Wait here.

924
01:09:30,904 --> 01:09:34,238
- David, what are you looking for?
- Just ...

925
01:09:37,286 --> 01:09:38,744
What are you doing?

926
01:09:40,956 --> 01:09:42,699
Will you marry me?

927
01:09:44,126 --> 01:09:45,585
What were you looking for?

928
01:09:46,587 --> 01:09:48,460
I thought I had a ring.

929
01:09:48,839 --> 01:09:51,412
It wouldn't have been the right one,
but it would have done for tonight.

930
01:09:52,905 --> 01:09:54,051
David.

931
01:09:55,971 --> 01:09:57,430
I'm serious.

932
01:10:03,187 --> 01:10:04,930
You're very sweet.

933
01:10:07,232 --> 01:10:08,976
What do you think?

934
01:10:15,824 --> 01:10:17,947
- Take me home.
- All right.

935
01:10:46,730 --> 01:10:48,354
They do need some looking after,

936
01:10:48,440 --> 01:10:50,682
but nothing that will require
too much work.

937
01:10:50,776 --> 01:10:53,231
Just leave them in your potting 
shed for a couple of weeks ...

938
01:10:53,445 --> 01:10:54,773
and they'll look after themselves.

939
01:10:54,863 --> 01:10:57,105
Fine, the potting shed.
Who does he think I am,

940
01:10:57,199 --> 01:10:58,942
Prince Rainier of Monaco?

941
01:11:03,121 --> 01:11:05,992
What if I got married
instead of going to college?

942
01:11:06,583 --> 01:11:08,291
- Married?
- Married.

943
01:11:10,378 --> 01:11:12,585
Well, it would depend
on who it was, of course.

944
01:11:12,672 --> 01:11:16,255
- Would it? That's interesting.
- Well, of course it would.

945
01:11:16,343 --> 01:11:18,585
I wouldn't want you married off
just for the sake of it.

946
01:11:18,929 --> 01:11:21,135
- Thanks.
- Has somebody asked you?

947
01:11:21,223 --> 01:11:23,215
- Yes.
- Who?

948
01:11:25,227 --> 01:11:28,228
- David?
- No. A man I just met walking his dog.

949
01:11:29,147 --> 01:11:31,817
- What did you tell him?
- Nothing yet.

950
01:11:33,026 --> 01:11:35,398
Do you have a choice, or is it too late?

951
01:11:36,238 --> 01:11:38,563
Of course she's got a choice!

952
01:11:39,574 --> 01:11:40,903
An interesting one, too?

953
01:11:40,992 --> 01:11:44,242
This is where you're supposed 
to say, "But what about Oxford?"

954
01:11:44,329 --> 01:11:46,618
Well, look at it another way.

955
01:11:46,706 --> 01:11:49,079
You wouldn't really need to 
go now, would you?

956
01:11:49,918 --> 01:11:53,750
I wouldn't need to go?
Would you like to expand on that?

957
01:11:53,964 --> 01:11:59,088
- You'd be looked after.
- All that Latin. All those essays!

958
01:12:00,470 --> 01:12:04,088
What was the point? Why didn't you just
send me prowling round nightclubs?

959
01:12:04,182 --> 01:12:06,341
It would have been less trouble
and I might have had more fun!

960
01:12:06,434 --> 01:12:09,554
I don't know about nightclubs,
I know about education.

961
01:12:09,646 --> 01:12:11,852
Anyway, looks like
it might have turned out ...

962
01:12:11,940 --> 01:12:13,399
for the best.
- How?

963
01:12:14,776 --> 01:12:17,611
He wouldn't want you if you 
were thick, now, would he?

964
01:12:18,697 --> 01:12:21,697
"May not an ass know
when the cart draws the horse?

965
01:12:21,783 --> 01:12:24,239
"Sings: Whoop, Jug! I love thee ..."

966
01:12:24,327 --> 01:12:27,328
When it says "sings",

967
01:12:27,414 --> 01:12:29,205
it means you sing the line.

968
01:12:31,835 --> 01:12:33,495
Never mind. Right. Lear.

969
01:12:33,586 --> 01:12:36,457
"Does any here know me?
This is not Lear.

970
01:12:36,548 --> 01:12:41,340
"Does Lear walk thus? Speak thus?
Where are his eyes?"

971
01:12:42,846 --> 01:12:47,472
"Waking? Who is it that
can tell me who I am?"

972
01:12:47,871 --> 01:12:49,765
Miss! Me. I can.

973
01:12:51,729 --> 01:12:54,896
- Jenny.
- What?

974
01:12:58,111 --> 01:12:59,605
Take it off.

975
01:13:01,781 --> 01:13:06,408
My God! Is that what I think it is?
I'm going to be a bridesmaid!

976
01:13:09,789 --> 01:13:11,283
You know the school 
rule on jewellery.

977
01:13:11,583 --> 01:13:13,243
Half the girls in this room
are wearing jewellery.

978
01:13:13,334 --> 01:13:14,994
Yes, but none of it's going
to ruin their lives.

979
01:13:18,256 --> 01:13:19,880
We have a difference of opinion
about that.

980
01:13:24,095 --> 01:13:26,301
How far advanced
are these ridiculous plans?

981
01:13:26,681 --> 01:13:29,254
Have you set a date?
Have you decided on a church?

982
01:13:29,893 --> 01:13:33,012
We won't be getting married 
in a church. David's Jewish.

983
01:13:35,106 --> 01:13:36,565
Jewish?

984
01:13:38,318 --> 01:13:39,812
He's a Jew?

985
01:13:41,738 --> 01:13:44,229
You are aware, I take it,
that the Jews killed our Lord?

986
01:13:44,574 --> 01:13:47,195
And you're aware, I suppose,
that our Lord was Jewish?

987
01:13:49,078 --> 01:13:51,154
I suppose he told you that.

988
01:13:52,874 --> 01:13:55,828
We're all very sorry about what
happened during the war,

989
01:13:55,918 --> 01:13:57,828
but that's absolutely no excuse ...

990
01:13:57,920 --> 01:14:00,874
for that sort of malicious
and untruthful propaganda.

991
01:14:01,883 --> 01:14:04,718
Anyway, I can see you're far more
in need of responsible advice ...

992
01:14:04,802 --> 01:14:06,344
than I realised.

993
01:14:07,722 --> 01:14:11,055
Nobody does anything worth doing
without a degree.

994
01:14:11,851 --> 01:14:15,350
Nobody does anything worth doing
with a degree. No woman, anyway.

995
01:14:16,064 --> 01:14:17,937
So what I do isn't worth doing?

996
01:14:18,024 --> 01:14:20,941
Or what Miss Stubbs does,
or Mrs. Wilson, or any of us here?

997
01:14:21,110 --> 01:14:22,902
Because none of us would be here
without a degree.

998
01:14:22,987 --> 01:14:24,695
You do realise that, don't you?
And yes, of course,

999
01:14:24,822 --> 01:14:26,898
studying is hard and boring ...
- Boring!

1000
01:14:27,742 --> 01:14:30,280
- I'm sorry?
- Studying is hard and boring.

1001
01:14:30,369 --> 01:14:33,703
Teaching is hard and boring. So
what you're telling me is to be bored,

1002
01:14:33,790 --> 01:14:35,912
and then bored and 
finally, bored again ...

1003
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:37,542
but this time for 
the rest of my life?

1004
01:14:37,835 --> 01:14:40,160
This whole stupid country is bored.

1005
01:14:40,671 --> 01:14:44,918
There's no life in it, or colour 
or fun. It's probably just as well ...

1006
01:14:45,009 --> 01:14:47,085
the Russians are going to drop
a nuclear bomb on us any day now.

1007
01:14:47,178 --> 01:14:51,341
So my choice is
to do something hard and boring,

1008
01:14:51,432 --> 01:14:54,267
or to marry my Jew ...

1009
01:14:54,602 --> 01:14:58,018
and go to Paris and Rome
and listen to jazz ...

1010
01:14:58,105 --> 01:15:01,973
and read and eat good food
in nice restaurants and have fun.

1011
01:15:02,818 --> 01:15:04,941
It's not enough to educate us
any more, Mrs. Walters.

1012
01:15:05,029 --> 01:15:06,903
You've got to tell us
why you're doing it.

1013
01:15:10,076 --> 01:15:13,990
It doesn't have to be teaching,
you know. There's the Civil Service.

1014
01:15:18,876 --> 01:15:21,367
I don't wish to be impertinent,
Mrs. Walters,

1015
01:15:22,255 --> 01:15:24,710
but it is an argument 
worth rehearsing.

1016
01:15:25,424 --> 01:15:29,374
You never know, someone else might want
to know the point of it all one day.

1017
01:16:19,103 --> 01:16:21,510
- Where did you find him?
- I can't tell you that.

1018
01:16:21,605 --> 01:16:23,562
- Why?
- I think he likes you. Do you like her?

1019
01:16:23,649 --> 01:16:26,816
"Yes, I do like her."
You do? You don't ...

1020
01:16:26,902 --> 01:16:29,572
You don't remember? It's Jenny.
You remember her from last time.

1021
01:16:29,655 --> 01:16:33,320
"No, I don't." Yes, you do!
Naughty thing. You ... Pardon?

1022
01:16:33,409 --> 01:16:36,991
That's revolting!
You stick to your own species.

1023
01:16:37,079 --> 01:16:39,950
He wants to kiss you, I think.

1024
01:16:40,040 --> 01:16:41,535
Is that naughty?

1025
01:16:42,459 --> 01:16:44,333
- We're engaged.
- Who is?

1026
01:16:44,795 --> 01:16:47,500
- No! Really?
- Yeah.

1027
01:16:47,590 --> 01:16:48,870
- Engaged?
- Show her.

1028
01:16:48,966 --> 01:16:51,124
- Yes! Look.
- Gosh!

1029
01:16:51,802 --> 01:16:54,507
- That's fantastic news!
- Thank you.

1030
01:16:55,472 --> 01:16:56,587
Congratulations.

1031
01:16:56,682 --> 01:16:59,766
I knew you'd see sense about 
university. You'll stay pretty now.

1032
01:17:00,102 --> 01:17:01,727
Can I still read?

1033
01:17:01,812 --> 01:17:03,935
Of course. But it doesn't have 
to be books now, does it?

1034
01:17:04,023 --> 01:17:07,226
Magazines will do just as well,
and you learn more from them, anyway.

1035
01:17:07,443 --> 01:17:09,815
- Helen.
- Well you won't be laughing, David,

1036
01:17:09,903 --> 01:17:12,192
when she goes all 
speccy and spotty.

1037
01:17:20,205 --> 01:17:22,827
Danny didn't seem very pleased
about our engagement.

1038
01:17:22,916 --> 01:17:25,787
I noticed that, too.
I thought he might be a bit jealous.

1039
01:17:26,712 --> 01:17:28,420
Jealous?

1040
01:17:28,505 --> 01:17:30,831
We're going to keep 
him away from you.

1041
01:17:37,973 --> 01:17:40,760
I mean, what is one supposed 
to order as a starter, anyway?

1042
01:17:40,851 --> 01:17:43,057
And how will I know
what is a starter and what isn't?

1043
01:17:43,145 --> 01:17:46,845
We've been through this, Dad. It'll be
quite clearly marked on the menu.

1044
01:17:48,275 --> 01:17:50,232
Can't the 3 of you just go
on your own and leave me here?

1045
01:17:50,319 --> 01:17:51,861
I'd be perfectly happy
with a tin of salmon.

1046
01:17:56,909 --> 01:17:58,735
- Hello.
- Hello.

1047
01:18:03,665 --> 01:18:05,907
Ready? I think you'll 
like this place, Jack.

1048
01:18:06,001 --> 01:18:08,159
Their wine list is as good
as anything I've seen in London.

1049
01:18:08,253 --> 01:18:09,913
Yes. Someone told me that.

1050
01:18:10,088 --> 01:18:12,414
David, probably.
Who else would it have been?

1051
01:18:15,093 --> 01:18:16,552
Madame.

1052
01:18:16,762 --> 01:18:18,505
I was hoping 
you'd take us in this.

1053
01:18:18,597 --> 01:18:20,636
You won't want to drive in 
anything else after tonight.

1054
01:18:20,974 --> 01:18:23,263
- Mind you, it drinks petrol.
- Yes.

1055
01:18:23,560 --> 01:18:26,134
I'm afraid we'll have to stop
on the way into town.

1056
01:18:26,855 --> 01:18:28,931
I feel like Eamonn Andrews.

1057
01:18:29,024 --> 01:18:30,435
- Is that a good thing?
- Eamonn Andrews

1058
01:18:30,525 --> 01:18:33,313
is the poshest person
that Jack can imagine being.

1059
01:18:48,502 --> 01:18:52,749
- How are you tonight, sir?
- Very well. Might as well fill her up.

1060
01:18:54,341 --> 01:18:56,832
I'm going to make a quick call.
I'll be 2 ticks.

1061
01:19:04,684 --> 01:19:07,389
Do you think I should offer
to help pay for the petrol?

1062
01:19:08,605 --> 01:19:10,064
Would he be insulted, 
do you think?

1063
01:19:11,274 --> 01:19:13,516
I know he said tonight was his treat,

1064
01:19:13,610 --> 01:19:15,935
but does that apply to 
the petrol, do you think?

1065
01:19:16,029 --> 01:19:17,986
I'm sure it does, Jack.

1066
01:19:25,413 --> 01:19:26,908
- No.
- Jack!

1067
01:19:27,290 --> 01:19:29,034
It just came off.

1068
01:19:38,176 --> 01:19:40,335
- Put it on my bill.
- Thank you, sir.

1069
01:19:40,595 --> 01:19:42,137
Cheers.

1070
01:19:45,308 --> 01:19:47,052
Jenny? Jenny.

1071
01:19:48,061 --> 01:19:49,555
Take us home.

1072
01:19:49,646 --> 01:19:52,398
- What's wrong?
- I'm afraid there's been ...

1073
01:19:52,482 --> 01:19:54,439
- Jenny's had a bit of a shock.
- What's happened?

1074
01:19:54,526 --> 01:19:59,104
It's just another one of David's
little muddles and misunderstandings.

1075
01:20:00,448 --> 01:20:02,406
I don't want to hear another word
from anybody. Take us home.

1076
01:20:02,492 --> 01:20:04,070
- Now.
- All right.

1077
01:20:15,338 --> 01:20:16,963
You can take care of this,
can't you, David?

1078
01:20:17,048 --> 01:20:18,507
Go inside, Dad.

1079
01:20:23,513 --> 01:20:27,427
"Mr. and Mrs. David Goldman."

1080
01:20:27,517 --> 01:20:30,222
"Mr. and Mrs. David ..." 
You're married!

1081
01:20:31,646 --> 01:20:33,354
Legally, yes, but I ...

1082
01:20:33,690 --> 01:20:36,263
- When were you going to tell me?
- Soon. It ...

1083
01:20:36,985 --> 01:20:39,357
It's just never seemed
like the right time.

1084
01:20:43,241 --> 01:20:45,115
You seemed so happy
and I was happy and ...

1085
01:20:45,201 --> 01:20:48,321
You were living with your wife
all this time.

1086
01:20:48,872 --> 01:20:51,197
Round the corner! Byron Avenue!

1087
01:20:51,291 --> 01:20:53,414
It's no wonder we kept bumping 
into each other, is it?

1088
01:20:53,501 --> 01:20:56,288
- What number?
- 34.

1089
01:21:02,093 --> 01:21:04,300
Don't be like this. Come on.

1090
01:21:08,057 --> 01:21:09,801
I have nothing.

1091
01:21:10,768 --> 01:21:14,137
I didn't take my exams. I ...

1092
01:21:14,230 --> 01:21:15,724
I left school!

1093
01:21:17,650 --> 01:21:19,726
Where's it all gone now?

1094
01:21:21,070 --> 01:21:22,944
I can get a divorce.

1095
01:21:26,117 --> 01:21:27,944
Everything will turn
 out for the best.

1096
01:21:37,962 --> 01:21:39,706
Go and tell them.

1097
01:21:42,550 --> 01:21:45,041
Go and tell them,
and then go and tell your wife.

1098
01:21:46,387 --> 01:21:47,846
They won't listen now.

1099
01:21:48,765 --> 01:21:54,768
All right? I'll come round tomorrow,
when everyone's feeling a bit calmer.

1100
01:21:55,063 --> 01:21:56,687
Please don't make me ...

1101
01:21:56,773 --> 01:21:58,812
Please don't make me tell them
on my own.

1102
01:21:59,692 --> 01:22:02,100
You owe me that much.
You owe them that much.

1103
01:22:02,320 --> 01:22:04,692
I owe them much more than that.

1104
01:22:11,245 --> 01:22:12,740
Hey.

1105
01:22:27,929 --> 01:22:30,764
2 minutes, and then I'll
come out and drag you in.

1106
01:23:28,823 --> 01:23:30,281
What's going on?

1107
01:23:34,078 --> 01:23:37,198
He's helping himself to some 
Dutch courage before facing you.

1108
01:23:38,916 --> 01:23:41,372
Stolen Dutch courage,
from the look of it.

1109
01:23:43,212 --> 01:23:45,833
He has something 
he has to tell you.

1110
01:23:57,727 --> 01:23:59,221
He just drove off!

1111
01:24:05,609 --> 01:24:07,269
Can you tell us?

1112
01:24:09,655 --> 01:24:11,233
Jenny, please!

1113
01:24:17,163 --> 01:24:19,451
I wouldn't worry about it
too much.

1114
01:24:22,084 --> 01:24:23,709
- When I found out ...
- Not now, Helen.

1115
01:24:33,637 --> 01:24:35,511
I tried to tell him.

1116
01:24:37,099 --> 01:24:40,931
I'm not speaking to him now,
if that's any consolation.

1117
01:24:43,772 --> 01:24:46,560
It's a funny world 
you people live in.

1118
01:24:47,776 --> 01:24:50,065
You both watched me carrying 
on with a married man ...

1119
01:24:50,154 --> 01:24:51,981
and you didn't think it was worth
saying anything about it.

1120
01:24:52,072 --> 01:24:53,732
Yes, well, if you want 
that conversation ...

1121
01:24:54,950 --> 01:24:57,358
You watched David and I
help ourselves to a map ...

1122
01:24:57,870 --> 01:24:59,530
and you didn't say much, either.

1123
01:25:27,441 --> 01:25:31,059
Come on, you, let's go. Good boy.

1124
01:25:37,993 --> 01:25:39,239
Hello.

1125
01:25:41,580 --> 01:25:45,031
Hello. Sorry, I think I've got the 
wrong number. I was looking for my ...

1126
01:25:45,125 --> 01:25:47,581
I wanted ... For my cello lesson.

1127
01:25:51,965 --> 01:25:53,923
No. Don't tell me.

1128
01:25:54,968 --> 01:25:56,511
Good God.

1129
01:25:57,596 --> 01:25:59,055
You're a child.

1130
01:26:03,060 --> 01:26:06,760
You didn't know
about any of this, presumably?

1131
01:26:10,776 --> 01:26:12,484
No. They never do.

1132
01:26:16,990 --> 01:26:20,655
You're not in the family way, are you?
Because that's happened before.

1133
01:26:26,375 --> 01:26:28,201
Thank God for that.

1134
01:26:32,047 --> 01:26:34,040
No. No. You stay here.

1135
01:26:46,311 --> 01:26:48,802
- Did you see her?
- Yes, I saw her.

1136
01:26:49,898 --> 01:26:51,938
I didn't talk to her.
There wasn't any need.

1137
01:26:52,025 --> 01:26:54,148
We have to have this out.

1138
01:26:55,737 --> 01:26:57,777
Well, if you won't do it, I will.
I'm still your father.

1139
01:26:57,864 --> 01:27:00,652
You're my father again now, 
are you? And what were you ...

1140
01:27:00,742 --> 01:27:03,150
when you encouraged me
to throw my life away?

1141
01:27:04,287 --> 01:27:06,031
Silly schoolgirls are always
getting seduced ...

1142
01:27:06,123 --> 01:27:08,032
by glamorous older men.
But what about you two?

1143
01:27:38,738 --> 01:27:40,316
Jenny?

1144
01:27:46,955 --> 01:27:48,533
Jenny.

1145
01:27:53,086 --> 01:27:54,794
Jenny, I'm sorry.

1146
01:28:03,138 --> 01:28:05,889
I know I've made a 
mess of everything.

1147
01:28:13,398 --> 01:28:15,723
All my life I've been scared ...

1148
01:28:17,569 --> 01:28:20,190
and I didn't want 
you to be scared.

1149
01:28:22,657 --> 01:28:24,484
That's why I wanted 
you to go to Oxford.

1150
01:28:26,661 --> 01:28:30,991
And then along came David
and he knew famous writers,

1151
01:28:31,082 --> 01:28:33,620
he knew how to get
to classical music concerts ...

1152
01:28:39,007 --> 01:28:41,545
But he wasn't 
who he said he was.

1153
01:28:44,220 --> 01:28:46,972
He wasn't who you 
said he was, either.

1154
01:28:52,562 --> 01:28:57,390
The other day, your mother 
and I were listening ...

1155
01:28:57,484 --> 01:29:00,687
to a programme on the radio
about CS Lewis,

1156
01:29:00,779 --> 01:29:04,942
and they said that he'd moved 
to Cambridge in 1954.

1157
01:29:09,037 --> 01:29:11,824
I said, 
"Well they've got that wrong."

1158
01:29:14,834 --> 01:29:17,290
Our Jenny wouldn't have 
his name in her book ...

1159
01:29:19,464 --> 01:29:21,622
if he'd moved to Cambridge.

1160
01:29:31,267 --> 01:29:33,556
There's a cup of tea
and some biscuits out here.

1161
01:30:07,428 --> 01:30:09,717
How do you think we can help?

1162
01:30:12,141 --> 01:30:15,973
I want to repeat my last year 
at school and take my exams.

1163
01:30:17,438 --> 01:30:21,816
I got the impression last time we spoke
that you didn't see the point of school,

1164
01:30:21,901 --> 01:30:24,059
or of me, or of any of us here.

1165
01:30:24,654 --> 01:30:26,278
I know. I was stupid.

1166
01:30:27,156 --> 01:30:30,490
The life I want, 
there's no shortcut.

1167
01:30:32,078 --> 01:30:34,913
I know now that I need 
to go to university.

1168
01:30:36,249 --> 01:30:39,166
It gives me absolutely
no pleasure whatsoever ...

1169
01:30:39,252 --> 01:30:42,371
to see our young schoolgirls
throwing their lives away.

1170
01:30:43,256 --> 01:30:46,126
Although, of course, you are not
one of our schoolgirls any more.

1171
01:30:46,217 --> 01:30:47,676
Through your own volition.

1172
01:30:48,678 --> 01:30:50,717
I suppose you think 
I'm a ruined woman.

1173
01:30:53,516 --> 01:30:55,508
You're not a woman.

1174
01:30:57,061 --> 01:30:59,682
No, I'm afraid I think that the 
offer of a place at this school ...

1175
01:30:59,772 --> 01:31:01,765
would be wasted on you.

1176
01:31:27,466 --> 01:31:29,091
Come in.

1177
01:31:31,137 --> 01:31:33,592
I didn't expect to see you again.

1178
01:31:41,522 --> 01:31:43,016
This is lovely.

1179
01:31:43,899 --> 01:31:46,083
All your books and pictures and ...

1180
01:31:48,237 --> 01:31:50,728
Paperbacks and postcards, Jenny.

1181
01:31:51,907 --> 01:31:53,450
That's all you need, isn't it?

1182
01:31:56,829 --> 01:31:58,703
Just somewhere to ...

1183
01:32:07,923 --> 01:32:11,791
I'm sorry I said those silly things.
I didn't understand.

1184
01:32:16,265 --> 01:32:18,174
Let's forget about it.

1185
01:32:26,734 --> 01:32:30,862
- A Burne-Jones.
- Do you like him?

1186
01:32:30,946 --> 01:32:33,235
I do. Still.

1187
01:32:35,409 --> 01:32:39,027
"Still"? You sound 
very old and wise.

1188
01:32:42,291 --> 01:32:45,624
I feel old, but not very wise.

1189
01:32:51,592 --> 01:32:53,086
Miss Stubbs, I need your help.

1190
01:32:59,475 --> 01:33:02,226
I was so hoping that's what 
you were going to say.

1191
01:33:52,945 --> 01:33:54,736
Thank you, Marjorie.

1192
01:34:10,087 --> 01:34:11,747
It's from Oxford.

1193
01:34:46,957 --> 01:34:49,033
"It is my pleasure to inform you ...

1194
01:34:49,126 --> 01:34:55,081
"that your application to read English
at Oxford has been accepted.

1195
01:34:55,173 --> 01:34:57,332
"On behalf of the Faculty of Arts,

1196
01:34:57,426 --> 01:35:01,506
"the staff of the university
look forward to welcoming you ..."

1197
01:35:20,490 --> 01:35:23,160
So I went to read English books,

1198
01:35:23,243 --> 01:35:25,449
and did my best to avoid 
the speccy, spotty fate ...

1199
01:35:25,537 --> 01:35:28,075
that Helen had predicted for me.

1200
01:35:28,165 --> 01:35:33,076
I probably looked as wide-eyed,
fresh and artless as any other student.

1201
01:35:33,962 --> 01:35:35,456
But I wasn't.

1202
01:35:37,257 --> 01:35:38,882
One of the boys I went out with,

1203
01:35:38,967 --> 01:35:40,509
and they really were boys,

1204
01:35:40,886 --> 01:35:43,922
once asked me to go 
to Paris with him.

1205
01:35:44,014 --> 01:35:48,759
And I told him I'd love to,
I was dying to see Paris,

1206
01:35:50,061 --> 01:35:51,935
as if I'd never been.
